{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Tree-of-Uncertain-Thought (TouT) (Mo and Xin, 2023) achieved even better results than ToT on the same challenges, with a 9% higher success rate on the Game of 24 and 3% on mini-crosswords.",
    "Finally, Inference-Exclusion-Prompting (IEP) (Tong et al., 2023) employs a combination of forward and backward reasoning to approximate human logic and delivered some of the best results on riddles and commonsense puzzles when combined with CoT, scoring 82% on puzzles-up from 81% with zero-shot CoT-and 79% on riddles, compared to 82% with zero-shot CoT.",
    "Graph topologies entail the following: Graphof-Thought(s) (GoT) (Besta et al., 2023; Lei et al., 2023) and Everything-of-Thought (XoT) (Ding et al., 2023) have been used to solve rulebased/deterministic puzzles.",
    "While GoT has shown poorer results compared to ToT, with a decrease ranging from 2% to 6% (Ding et al., 2023), XoT has been recognized as the most effective method for these puzzles.",
    "XoT integrates Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS) with LLMs for enhanced thought generation, achieving improvements in results from 53% to 69% compared to ToT."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
